WEBVTT

00:00.800 --> 00:03.166
(loud, overlapping chatter)

00:09.270 --> 00:11.409
Look, I am the one who
is suffering here.

00:11.440 --> 00:13.169
Oh, yes, tell us
your troubles.

00:13.210 --> 00:15.030
I am handling all
of Will's cases,

00:15.080 --> 00:16.274
and now we've lost
Caitlin, too.

00:16.310 --> 00:18.141
Look, we put someone else into
Will's seat, that's what we do.

00:18.180 --> 00:19.579
Excuse me. I'm
sitting right here.

00:19.620 --> 00:20.746
There is no
"Will's seat."

00:20.780 --> 00:21.576
You're not here as a lawyer.

00:21.620 --> 00:23.417
You might as well
not be here at all.

00:23.450 --> 00:25.315
That is not the subject
of this discussion.

00:26.690 --> 00:29.352
Someone spoke to the
bar disciplinary board.

00:29.390 --> 00:31.722
Someone said Will was
here working on cases.

00:31.760 --> 00:34.627
Now, I'm not going to
do anything so dramatic

00:34.660 --> 00:36.298
as to ask, "Who was it?"

00:36.330 --> 00:38.195
But I will say this.
If you have an issue

00:38.230 --> 00:39.834
with the way we're running
this firm, you come to me.

00:39.870 --> 00:41.735
You do not stab Will
in the back.

00:41.770 --> 00:44.364
You don't lie
to the disciplinary board...

00:44.410 --> 00:45.661
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.

00:45.710 --> 00:48.304
Look, I know
nobody wants to respond

00:48.340 --> 00:50.479
because we don't want
to look like Judases,

00:50.510 --> 00:52.478
but Will is working on cases.

00:52.520 --> 00:54.112
No, I'm updating

00:54.150 --> 00:55.777
associates on the
background of my cases.

00:55.820 --> 00:56.684
What?!

00:56.720 --> 00:57.414
DAVID:
Oh, come on.

00:57.450 --> 00:59.213
You call me
an ethical midget?

00:59.260 --> 01:00.613
(loud, overlapping shouting)

01:01.720 --> 01:03.688
Just a minute!
Wait a minute!

01:03.730 --> 01:06.790
We disagree with each
other, we keep it in-house!

01:06.830 --> 01:09.765
you want to backstab someone,
do it right here.

01:09.800 --> 01:11.768
Okay, I disagree. There.

01:11.800 --> 01:14.291
And I urge the equity partners
to replace Will

01:14.340 --> 01:15.534
until such time...

01:15.570 --> 01:18.232
Then marshal the equity partner
votes, and call a meeting.

01:18.270 --> 01:20.238
Are we done here?
No.

01:20.280 --> 01:21.702
Alicia's asked for a raise.

01:21.740 --> 01:22.877
(people sighing)

01:22.910 --> 01:24.775
I am advocating
a ten percent bump.

01:24.810 --> 01:27.711
No, you have a dozen
third-year associates who will

01:27.750 --> 01:29.581
be asking for the
same exact thing.

01:29.620 --> 01:31.588
Then we lose her.
And how do
you know that?

01:31.620 --> 01:33.417
Because he's got
a dog in the fight.
We only want

01:33.460 --> 01:35.712
Alicia because of her
ties to her husband.

01:35.760 --> 01:37.387
No, we want her
because she's good.

01:37.430 --> 01:38.783
(laughs)
We're gonna take
your word for it?

01:38.830 --> 01:40.798
ELI:
Look, look, we all know
we're gonna compromise.

01:40.830 --> 01:41.854
Can we just compromise?

01:41.900 --> 01:44.095
(loud, overlapping chatter)

01:47.870 --> 01:49.906
Who do you
think leaked it?

01:49.940 --> 01:51.737
Could be any one of them.

01:51.770 --> 01:54.830
Good thing they don't like
each other, or I'd be dead.

01:54.880 --> 01:57.098
Where you headed?
Court.

01:57.810 --> 01:59.846
Why? You don't have
a case today.

01:59.880 --> 02:01.347
DIANE:
Diane Lockhart.

02:01.380 --> 02:04.838
L-O-C-K-H-A-R-T.

02:04.890 --> 02:07.711
JACK:
And can you describe
what happened,

02:07.760 --> 02:09.284
Ms. Lockhart?

02:09.330 --> 02:11.218
Yes. I was walking
from my car

02:11.260 --> 02:16.721
when I saw you in the lobby,
serving a subpoena to that man.

02:16.770 --> 02:18.192
JACK:
And did you hear me
announce myself?

02:18.230 --> 02:20.266
Ah, yes. I heard you say,

02:20.300 --> 02:22.268
"Mr. Dobbs,
you have been served."

02:22.310 --> 02:24.835
Then what happened?

02:24.870 --> 02:26.804
In your own words,
Ms. Lockhart.

02:28.810 --> 02:32.268
Uh, well, uh,
that man tried to punch you,

02:32.320 --> 02:34.276
and then you threw him

02:34.320 --> 02:36.288
against the wall.
In a manly fashion?

02:36.320 --> 02:38.880
Yes, I would say so.

02:38.920 --> 02:41.411
He says I threw the first punch.
That's why he's suing me.

02:41.460 --> 02:43.428
Uh, that is not
what I observed.

02:43.460 --> 02:45.781
You two know each other.
That's why she's saying that.

02:45.830 --> 02:48.754
Do you and I know each other,
Ms. Lockhart?

02:48.800 --> 02:50.859
Uh, well, you

02:50.900 --> 02:52.436
served me with a subpoena,

02:52.470 --> 02:54.631
so I guess to that extent,
we know each other.

02:54.670 --> 02:55.762
JACK:
Thank you, Ms. Lockhart.

02:55.800 --> 02:58.598
Your presence here in
small-claims court is a breath

02:58.640 --> 02:59.572
of fresh air.

02:59.610 --> 03:00.679
(gavelbangs)
Objection.

03:00.710 --> 03:01.802
Overruled.

03:01.840 --> 03:03.705
And I will ask you to proceed,

03:03.750 --> 03:05.809
Mrs. Florrick.
So the video

03:05.850 --> 03:07.511
was taken from the back
of the snowmobile?

03:07.550 --> 03:09.484
Uh, yes,
my-my wife was taking it.

03:09.520 --> 03:11.385
That's just
her cell phone camera.

03:11.420 --> 03:12.956
(engine rewing)

03:12.990 --> 03:14.480
And that's you driving?

03:14.520 --> 03:17.489
Yes. Up at the Rollins
Savanna Forest Preserve.

03:17.530 --> 03:18.656
(laughter on video)

03:18.690 --> 03:20.396
ALICIA:
Then what happened?

03:20.430 --> 03:23.820
The snowmobile-- it just started
changing directions.

03:23.870 --> 03:25.861
WOMAN:
Okay, Grant, slow down.

03:26.970 --> 03:28.835
ALICIA: _ _
Were you steering it
toward the trees?

03:28.870 --> 03:30.007
GRANT:
No.

03:30.040 --> 03:31.462
WOMAN:
What are you doing?!

03:31.510 --> 03:32.829
_ GRANT:
The steering column locked, and

03:32.880 --> 03:34.006
I...

03:34.040 --> 03:35.871
WOMAN:
It's not funny. Stop.

03:35.910 --> 03:37.741
I couldn't budge it.

03:37.780 --> 03:39.270
Please slow down!

03:39.320 --> 03:41.948
Grant, slow down! Please!

03:41.980 --> 03:43.982
(woman screaming, thudding)

03:51.030 --> 03:52.998
And what happened
to your wife?

03:53.030 --> 03:54.998
(clears throat)

03:55.030 --> 03:56.861
She was in a coma for a week,

03:56.900 --> 03:58.891
and then she...

04:00.940 --> 04:02.999
She... she didn't make it.

04:05.040 --> 04:07.577
And that's why you're suing
Snow Plain, the makers

04:07.610 --> 04:08.736
of your snowmobile?

04:08.780 --> 04:10.042
Yes. Uh,
I've never

04:10.080 --> 04:11.877
sued anyone in my life.

04:11.910 --> 04:13.844
Never had much use
for the courts.

04:13.880 --> 04:14.710
My-my parents told me,

04:14.750 --> 04:16.911
"If you have a problem
with someone,

04:16.950 --> 04:19.680
then, you say it to his face,"
but my wife...

04:19.720 --> 04:21.688
(crying)

04:21.720 --> 04:23.984
She was the best
thing in my life.

04:24.030 --> 04:25.918
JUDGE:
Okay, let me interrupt
right there.

04:25.960 --> 04:27.689
Mrs. Florrick, Mr. Hines,

04:27.730 --> 04:29.698
why don't you come up
here, and we'll talk?

04:29.730 --> 04:31.061
Here's the deal.

04:31.100 --> 04:33.398
First of all, good
morning to you all.

04:33.440 --> 04:34.566
ALL:
Good morning.

04:34.600 --> 04:35.737
We're going into chambers

04:35.770 --> 04:36.634
for a bench-supervised
negoﬁaﬂon.

04:36.670 --> 04:38.399
HINES:
Your Honor,
that's not necessary.

04:38.440 --> 04:39.577
Counselor Hines, it is.

04:39.610 --> 04:41.430
Your case here
is obVIously

04:41.480 --> 04:42.970
to delay
until Mr. Duverney gives up.

04:43.010 --> 04:45.547
That's not true!
And I'm not gonna
be a party to that.

04:45.580 --> 04:47.775
There are no _real
legal issues to dispute,

04:47.820 --> 04:48.809
so here is my order.

04:48.850 --> 04:51.910
Marshal your settlement
arguments and meet me

04:51.950 --> 04:53.451
in chambers in one hour.
Understood?

04:53.490 --> 04:55.879
ALL:
Yes, Your Honor.
(gavelbangs)

04:55.920 --> 04:58.059
I think I might try my hand
at this lavwering.

04:58.090 --> 05:00.354
Very impressive.

05:00.400 --> 05:02.095
So I have to thank you.

05:02.130 --> 05:05.327
There's an art show, or
something or other,near here.

05:05.370 --> 05:06.894
(laughing):
You're not really into art?

05:06.940 --> 05:09.363
No, but I don't
actively dislike it.
(laughs)

05:09.410 --> 05:11.970
I'm sorry, but I have
to head back to work.

05:12.010 --> 05:14.001
But you do have
to have lunch.

05:16.950 --> 05:19.919
Actually, I think
someone's waiting for you?

05:19.950 --> 05:23.113
Okay, then, tonight.

05:23.150 --> 05:24.686
I'll call you.

05:24.720 --> 05:26.711
(birds singing)

05:28.020 --> 05:30.022
GRANT:
You thinking of buying?

05:32.730 --> 05:34.891
I don't know what I'm thinking.
Everything's so expensive

05:34.930 --> 05:35.954
these days.

05:36.000 --> 05:38.389
Well, you know one thing
I learned is, life is short.

05:38.430 --> 05:39.966
You get a chance to bring
yourself some pleasure,

05:40.000 --> 05:41.365
you should do it.

05:41.400 --> 05:45.359
Even ifI had the money,
I... I don't know.

05:45.410 --> 05:46.877
It's my old house.

05:46.910 --> 05:48.878
Doesn't make sense
to go bacloNards.

05:48.910 --> 05:51.140
Hmm. Look at me.

05:51.180 --> 05:53.375
I'd give anything
to go bacloNard.

05:53.420 --> 05:56.810
MAN:
Mrs. Florrick, the judge
is ready for you now.

05:56.850 --> 05:58.112
Here we go.

05:58.150 --> 05:59.811
What is it about glasses?

05:59.860 --> 06:02.010
I seem to walk into a room,
and they disappear.

06:02.060 --> 06:03.925
HINES:
Your Honor, this is not
just about one suit.

06:03.960 --> 06:05.689
This is about the class action

06:05.730 --> 06:07.095
that Lockhart & Gardner has
in the wings...

06:07.130 --> 06:09.667
No, it is about one suit.
We're asking for $5 million

06:09.700 --> 06:11.065
for pain and suffering,
loss of spousal support...

06:11.100 --> 06:12.829
JUDGE:
You know, I used
to carry around

06:12.870 --> 06:15.065
three or four pair of glasses.

06:15.100 --> 06:17.068
At the end of the day,

06:17.110 --> 06:19.977
I was like a drunk
looking for bottles. Ugh!

06:20.010 --> 06:21.932
You're paying, Mr. Hines.

06:21.980 --> 06:24.676
By the evidence I've
seen, you're paying.

06:24.710 --> 06:27.747
The only question is,
how much?
But you haven't
seen this evidence.

06:27.780 --> 06:29.919
What is it?
Grant Duverney's
medical report.

06:29.950 --> 06:32.009
From 2009.
Before the accident.

06:32.050 --> 06:34.780
Yes, but after his career as
a professional hockey player.

06:34.820 --> 06:36.856
What does that have to do
with anything?

06:36.890 --> 06:38.881
Modiﬁed comparative
negngnce.

06:38.930 --> 06:40.989
If your client contributed
to the accident--

06:41.030 --> 06:42.895
in fact-- if he
contributed more

06:42.930 --> 06:45.023
than 50% to the accident--
then he can't sue us.

06:45.070 --> 06:46.833
You're saying that
he's responsible

06:46.870 --> 06:48.599
for his wife's death?
I'm saying,
given his mental capacity

06:48.640 --> 06:50.938
after 86 games as a professional
hockey player--

06:50.970 --> 06:52.801
body checks and fights--

06:52.840 --> 06:55.035
he had no business getting
on that snowmobile.

06:55.080 --> 06:57.071
Your Honor, this...
is despicable.

06:57.110 --> 06:59.749
And yet legal, Counselor.

06:59.780 --> 07:01.441
You're saying, Counselor Hines,

07:01.480 --> 07:03.619
that the plaintiff
caused his own accident

07:03.650 --> 07:05.015
by steering into a tree?

07:05.050 --> 07:06.517
I'm saying, it contributed.

07:06.560 --> 07:08.812
The plaintiff's
apparent condition--

07:08.860 --> 07:10.555
chronic traumatic
encephalopathy--

07:10.590 --> 07:12.626
was more than 50%
of the problem.

07:12.660 --> 07:14.491
Okay.

07:14.530 --> 07:16.020
I'll be ordering an independent

07:16.060 --> 07:18.995
neurological evaluation
on Mr. Duverney.

07:19.030 --> 07:21.032
We'll see where
that takes us.

07:23.070 --> 07:25.038
_ JULIUS:
Ba5ically, we're in trouble.

07:25.070 --> 07:27.038
DIANE:
How can we be in trouble?
We were in negotiations on this.

07:27.080 --> 07:28.968
They're going after
his hockey career.

07:29.010 --> 07:31.501
And Judge Rigby is
giving them some rope.
So there's truth

07:31.550 --> 07:33.108
in their charges?

07:33.150 --> 07:35.971
Grant played 86 games
as a pro hockey player,

07:36.020 --> 07:39.717
and in his 86th start, he
was in a fight on the ice,

07:39.760 --> 07:40.852
and ended up in the hospital.

07:40.890 --> 07:43.120
He never played again. His
motor functions were impaired.

07:43.160 --> 07:44.718
So, there might be truth.

07:44.760 --> 07:46.694
And how did we not
see this coming?

07:46.730 --> 07:47.651
(man clearing his throat)

07:47.700 --> 07:49.019
Do you have a minute?

07:51.730 --> 07:54.699
So, this was my case.
Yes.

07:54.740 --> 07:58.062
And supposedly, a winner.
Which it still is, but I have

07:58.110 --> 08:01.807
some strategic information
I could... share with you.

08:01.840 --> 08:04.104
_ If it weren't for the _
restrictions of your suspen5ion?

08:04.150 --> 08:06.812
Yes, which, as I understand it,
prevents me from talking about

08:06.850 --> 08:09.148
future strategy,
but not...
Past. That would
be updating?

08:09.180 --> 08:10.784
Which is within my rights.

08:10.820 --> 08:13.983
Yet, we seem to be
in here whispering.

08:14.020 --> 08:16.215
(whispers):
Consulting.

08:16.260 --> 08:18.285
What do you got?

08:18.330 --> 08:19.695
Bring hockey into it.

08:19.730 --> 08:21.721
Into our case?

08:21.760 --> 08:25.161
Yes. Their defense is based on
modified comparative negligence.

08:25.200 --> 08:28.169
If our client is responsible
for 50% of his accident,

08:28.200 --> 08:30.998
he loses, but...

08:31.040 --> 08:34.100
If professional hockey is
responsible for his injuries,

08:34.140 --> 08:34.936
then he can collect.

08:34.980 --> 08:37.107
And this is your
suggested strategy?

08:37.150 --> 08:38.799
It is.

08:38.850 --> 08:39.839
Well, Diane,

08:39.880 --> 08:41.973
this is a mistake.

08:42.020 --> 08:43.146
Hockey will never pay.

08:43.190 --> 08:45.112
To pay would be to
open up themselves

08:45.150 --> 08:47.118
to hundreds of lawsuits
from former players.

08:47.160 --> 08:49.549
It's part of the strategy.
Pull hockey into this.

08:49.590 --> 08:50.818
They'll want to bury it

08:50.860 --> 08:52.828
quickly and quietly.
We found our deep pocket.

08:52.860 --> 08:55.249
Yes, and in addition,
the APHL lawyers will delay.

08:55.300 --> 08:57.120
So we'll get
a three-month continuance

08:57.170 --> 08:59.092
to build our case.
You want me on it?

08:59.130 --> 09:00.688
DIANE:
Um, I do, but a low priority.

09:00.740 --> 09:02.901
And, Alicia,
do you have a moment?
Yes.

09:07.010 --> 09:10.673
So, we want to keep
you happy here, Alicia.

09:10.710 --> 09:14.043
We value all your hard work
these past few months.

09:14.080 --> 09:15.240
Thank you.

09:15.280 --> 09:17.145
Given that, the equity
partners have agreed

09:17.190 --> 09:19.886
on paper to a
bump in your pay.

09:19.920 --> 09:21.057
Great.

09:21.090 --> 09:22.978
Uh, yes, but we want
to be clear.

09:23.030 --> 09:24.884
There are 11 other
third-year associates,

09:24.930 --> 09:26.921
so, we can't afford
an across-the-board raise.

09:26.960 --> 09:28.655
I understand.

09:28.700 --> 09:30.065
So, here's what we're offering.

09:32.800 --> 09:36.133
I know, it's not as much
as you think you deserve,

09:36.170 --> 09:37.637
but take it as a demonstration

09:37.670 --> 09:39.672
of_ our confidence
in your future.

09:41.410 --> 09:43.799
KALIN DA:
Hey.

09:43.850 --> 09:45.704
Thought you might
want something.

09:45.750 --> 09:47.047
No, thanks.

09:47.080 --> 09:48.616
You don't know who's leaking

09:48.650 --> 09:50.686
to the disciplinary board
about me, do you?

09:50.720 --> 09:52.915
No. You want me to look?

09:52.960 --> 09:54.279
No. Just if you hear anything.

09:54.320 --> 09:56.720
You in trouble?

09:56.760 --> 09:58.751
Sticking to the letter
of the law.

09:58.790 --> 10:00.758
You gonna leave me
here with two beers?

10:00.800 --> 10:03.121
You'll find somebody.

10:18.710 --> 10:19.938
KALIN DA:
What's up?

10:19.980 --> 10:21.140
You want a beer?

10:25.190 --> 10:26.282
No. Thanks.

10:26.320 --> 10:27.810
You're sure?

10:27.860 --> 10:30.021
It's open.

10:32.860 --> 10:34.851
Kalinda, I...

10:35.860 --> 10:37.862
I'm sorry.

10:39.170 --> 10:41.695
I can't help it. I want
to move on, but I...

10:41.740 --> 10:43.002
Yeah, I... I get it.

10:43.040 --> 10:44.166
Look, we're working together.

10:44.210 --> 10:45.131
That's good enough, isn't it?

10:45.170 --> 10:47.331
Yeah.

10:47.380 --> 10:50.178
It's just not
easy for me...
It's okay, Alicia.

10:50.210 --> 10:52.872
I get it.

11:06.330 --> 11:08.321
I'm Louis Canning, Your Honor.

11:08.360 --> 11:10.089
I'll be representing
the interests

11:10.130 --> 11:11.392
of the All Professional
Hockey League.

11:11.430 --> 11:13.398
JUDGE:
Welcome, Mr. Canning; you
saw the amended complaint?

11:13.440 --> 11:16.238
I did, Your Honor, and a baroque
piece of work it is.

11:16.270 --> 11:17.703
Baroque, and yet,

11:17.740 --> 11:19.207
if Snow Plain insists

11:19.240 --> 11:21.800
on a modified comparative
negligence defense,

11:21.840 --> 11:23.148
I see no other option

11:23.180 --> 11:25.045
than to offer the plaintiff
a chance to combine

11:25.080 --> 11:28.049
charges of negligence. Darn.

11:28.080 --> 11:29.342
Yes, Your Honor, we accept
the modified complaint.

11:29.380 --> 11:31.211
Then I expect you'll be
asking for an extension?

11:31.250 --> 11:34.083
Oh, no, no,
we're ready to go.

11:34.120 --> 11:35.883
Right now.

11:36.930 --> 11:38.227
In fact, we welcome the chance

11:38.260 --> 11:40.251
to defend the honor
of professional hockey.

11:42.830 --> 11:43.819
He thinks
you're not prepared.

11:43.870 --> 11:47.499
Excuse me, Will,
you can't be saying anything.

11:47.540 --> 11:50.361
We need to move quickly
on all fronts.

11:50.410 --> 11:51.763
I'll get on with Kalinda.

12:03.250 --> 12:05.013
ANNOUNCER: They still can't
clear it, as Olsen keeps it in,

12:06.190 --> 12:08.351
Duverney, in the corner,
tied up right now with Raker.

12:08.390 --> 12:10.085
And here we go.

12:10.130 --> 12:12.758
KALINDA: That's Cameron Raker,
Minnesota's enforcer.

12:12.800 --> 12:15.223
You just had to expect this.

12:15.260 --> 12:17.296
A lot of bad blood between
these two teams.

12:17.330 --> 12:18.194
Oh, my!

12:18.230 --> 12:19.959
Raker landed one square on.

12:20.000 --> 12:21.888
He's flat on...

12:21.940 --> 12:25.103
KALINDA: There was a criminal
battery investigation in 2009,

12:25.140 --> 12:27.074
but charges
were never brought.

12:27.110 --> 12:28.236
DIANE: It would be helpful
to get that investigation.

12:28.280 --> 12:29.338
I'm on it.

12:29.380 --> 12:30.506
